rketing and Law at the University of KwaZulu-Natal and after graduating, he worked at Unilever for four years; spending some time at Unilever Holland. Thereafter he worked for the Spar Group, then Chemspec Paint. He went on to become the marketing director at Dunlop Tyres and currently he is the Sales Director at SA Natural Products. Aissing said that in his free time he plays rugby and has played over 100 games for Collegians 1st Rugby XV. “I have also played 1st Division Club Cricket for Durban Varsity and I still enjoy social rugby. I have played numerous games for SA Legends and I also enjoy reading, spending time with family, playing golf and exercising,” said Aissing.  Nicholas Tyler, who is currently the director of marketing at GHS, is no stranger to the GHS family and, like his predecessor, grew up in the Glenwood area and attended Penzance Primary School. In 2000, he was head prefect at GHS where he was awarded the Grant Robertson Leadership Excellence Award, Academic Honours, Colours for Drama, Drum Major in the Band (1996 to 2000) and he was a South African representative of the Lion’s St Lucia Wildlife and Leadership Youth Camp in 2000. He went on to study a Bachelor of Medical Science Honours at the University of KwaZulu-Natal and recently, successfully completed his PGCE at Stadio. “Since 2005, I have been running my own business – NET Projects – which is essentially a construction and project implementation company building RDP housing for disadvantaged people. In my free time, I play rugby, golf and squash and I am an active member of the Durban Caledonian Society Pipe Band,” said Tyler.